e from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Grelle","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Grell  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Grell","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt, Claus, Dietrich, Franz, Guenter.","German: nickname for an irritable, irascible person, from Middle High German <i>grel</i> ‘rough, angry’.","German: metonymic occupational name from Middle High German <i>grelle</i> ‘spiked instrument; fork, spear’ for a user or maker."]}]},{"name":"Emma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   containing the word <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Emma de Grelle was born in 1152, in Dalton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Albert \"Juvenis\" de Grelle, Baron of Manchester, was 32 and her mother, Isabel Basset, was 30. She had at least 1 son with Sir Robert Fitz Henry De Scarisbrick. She died in 1172, in Dalton, Lancashire, England, at the age of 20."},"et":{"1152–1172 aged 15 - 24":"1152–1172","1152–1172":"1152–1172","1173–1230":"1173–1230","1123–1185":"1123–1185","1170–1238":"1170–1238","1120–1180":"1120–1180","1122–1185":"1122–1185","1238":"1238","1172 aged 15 - 24":"1172","1123":"1123","1122":"1122","112